Anonymous Sun 06 May 2018 23:57:47 No.15607546 Report
Quoted By: >>15607704 >>15607711 >>15607922
>>15606193
Hey, good job on this one Comfy. I enjoyed it.

Some critiques:
While your descriptions are great at describing action and movement throughout the scene, I think you could benefit a little more from taking some time to describe their facial expressions, both in and out of conversations. It is a character focused story after all, and with it being in second person, we the reader can't exactly get inside her head to tell exactly what she's thinking or feeling at the moment. Taking a little time to embellish on these details helps flush out the character and instill a sense of emotion into the scene, and I don't mean explicitly stating "She looked sad", but more along the lines of "Aurora frowned, her gaze slowly falling to the table as a shallow sigh racked her body." It feels more complex, more natural, to me at least, as long as you can keep it contained without it getting too purple-prosy. Throw in a few 'toothy grins', 'cocked eyebrows', and whatnot into some dialogue and see how you like it. Experiment a little until you get to a level of detail that you feel both adds to the scene without making it too wordy. Or you could do none of this, if you feel it detracts from your writing technique or makes it too complex and time-consuming. I am just a random retard who doesn't do much writing, after all.

Big major complaints:
>dating for 6 months
>Anniversary

basics n shit
start with perspective and basic shapes then move onto shading

after that start doing quick figure sketches to study anatomy

you'll get it eventually, but it'll take a shitload of practice. If you're doing digital get a tablet, I personally prefer wacom intuos or if you're strapped for cash a used bamboo fun is a pretty solid pickup. if traditional, get yourself a 120 page or more sketchbook and just go for it. Get yourself a good set of pencils as well, you can start with just a standard mechanical but if you're serious, get something like faber castell. you'll want 6B to 6H and a kneaded eraser. Holy shit I love those fuckers. Once you're good enough get a really good scanner so you can share and/or sell like ECMajor and Ruaidri do

A good warm-up and practice is to take old magazines and newspapers with lots of pictures and draw over the pictures in pen, breaking down any figures and images into simple shapes and line skeletons. Should help you understand proportions, posing, and the basics of figure drawing. Keep at it, and slowly work in more detail as you do, but try not to trace anything. Then after you're comfortable, trying doing the same thing but on a blank sheet of paper, and see where you end up. Easy.
